Hope and loyal friends are said to cling to her when she changes her garb and leaves the horne of greatness Hope and loyal friends are consolations of adversity, so that Horace must mean not that they go with Fortune when· she deseris a man, but that they cling to him, to his changed estate as to his anchanged. Yet if this is the case, in what sense is she said to be ‘inimica'l On whom does she frown? A man deserted by Fortune, suffering under the illtreatment of Fortune, is a common picture, but it is a conception of For- tune which, is it suits the earlier stanzas oi the Ode, is at variance with the general tone ol this one. Fortune, according to this, does not drive the great man from his palace, nor fly from him and leave him in it to calamity, but goes with him. She ‘changes her garb‚' but only as he would himself: it is the common Roman habit ol putting on a sad-coloured dress in a time of missortune (cp. Epod. 9. 28 tpunico Lugubre mutavit sagum ’).
